SSL/TLS Certificate

A website uses an SSL/TLS certificate to:

Prove its identity.
Encrypt data in transit.
Build user trust.

Without a valid certificate, browsers typically display security warnings.

Real-World Example

When you visit:

https://github.com

Your browser:

Resolves the domain name using DNS.
Establishes a TCP connection.
Performs a TLS handshake.
Sends encrypted HTTP requests.
Receives encrypted responses.



Linux Commands
View HTTP Response Headers
curl -I https://google.com

Download a Web Page
curl https://example.com

Test an HTTPS Connection
curl -v https://google.com
Show TLS Certificate Details
openssl s_client -connect google.com:443

Press Ctrl + C to exit after viewing the certificate details.



Advantages of HTTPS
Encrypts data.
Protects usernames and passwords.
Prevents eavesdropping.
Verifies server identity.
Builds user trust.
Required by many modern web features.


